<SECOND>PM-Germany-Freedom Flight,0730</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germans Say Lack of Freedom and Economic Reforms Forced Them
to Leave</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Refugess</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TIEFENBACH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For 12 years, <PERSON> Guenter </PERSON> <PERSON> Bachmann </PERSON> worked as a loading dock supervisor at a state cooperative in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Then he got tired of not being able to say what he really thought. Last week, <PERSON> Bachmann </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Sabina </PERSON>, packed the family car with a few belongings and headed for <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> to join thousands of their countrymen streaming to the West over <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s border with <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>. `` It just hit me all of a sudden,'' the heavy-set 33-year-old <PERSON> Bachmann </PERSON> said outside a refugee camp in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s picturesque Bavarian countryside. `` I just finally had enough of never being able to say what I really thought, and there was no hint it was ever going to change.'' The estimated 14,000 East Germans who fled to the West via <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> in the past week come from all walks of life, ranging from laborers to tradesmen, from bakers to doctors and lawyers. Their exodus occurred amid increasing pressure for democratic reforms across <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, which has rejected the need for economic and political reforms under way in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> enjoys the best standard of living in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc, but shortages are an aggravating fact of daily life. Dissent quickly is silenced by security forces. Demonstrators demanding democracy routinely are beaten and jailed. Public dissatisfaction in the hard-line <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> nation of 16 million has mounted steadily. According to the West German Ministry for Inter-German Affairs, 74 percent of East Germans who have come to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> since August left because of a lack of freedom of expression and human rights. The discontent is causing <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> to lose some of its best workers in the country's biggest drain of talent since the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall went up in 1961. A ministry report published Thursday said 55 percent of East German refugees who have come to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> since August are between 18 and 30 years old, and 86 percent have high levels of job training. The survey said the majority enjoyed relatively comfortable lifestyles in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Nearly all owned a television, more than half of them color. Sixty-one percent owned cars, according to the report. But it was n't enough to keep them in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. `` When you read the state-owned newspapers, you feel like they really must take you for a fool,'' said <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Dengler </PERSON>, a chemical engineering student from <LOCATION> Leipzig </LOCATION>, who was interviewed after crossing into the West. `` The paper declares one production success after another and <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s commitment to human rights, while in reality you still have to wait 15 years for what passes for a car and land in jail if you show a banner praising Soviet glasnost.'' <PERSON> Hermann </PERSON> <PERSON> Knorr </PERSON>, 25, said he decided to leave out of frustration at not being able to change the system. `` You talk and talk in small groups and nothing ever happens,'' said <PERSON> Knorr </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> member who was close to finishing a law degree in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>. `` When I finally gave up and tried to organize -LRB- illegal -RRB- discussion groups, the state security paid me a visit.'' <PERSON> Knorr </PERSON> said he had wanted to stay in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> but `` lost all hope.'' Many young refugees said the aggravations of daily life became unbearable when added to severe travel restrictions to the West and lack of free expression. `` When I applied for an apartment of my own, I was told that the wait would be 10 years,'' said <PERSON> Heidi </PERSON> <PERSON> Brueckl </PERSON>, who was a medical assistant in <LOCATION> Gera </LOCATION>. `` I get along with my parents all right, but I do n't think I need to live with them until I'm 35. I want to be able to live my own life.'' <PERSON> Anna </PERSON> <PERSON> Schroetter </PERSON>, a 27-year-old textile worker form <LOCATION> Leipzig </LOCATION>, said she was proud of some of the achievements of her country, especially social programs that guaranteed free day care and other services. `` But what good is day care and kindergarten when your children are drilled full of ideological nonsense? What good are guarantees of a job when you have no real say in the work place?'' she asked.
