<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rock' n' roll pioneer <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said Friday he's donating hundreds of videotapes, films and other memorabilia for a music museum in a 30-story pyramid being built along the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. `` I've got a great collection of stuff to share,'' <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>'s announcement was to have kicked off a night of parades, music and fireworks to mark the start of construction of the $ 56 million pyramid, intended as the centerpiece of a $ 200 million tourist theme park billed as a musical Disneyland. Then it rained, and the party was postponed 24 hours, leaving thousands of would-be revelers wandering aimlessly past soggy beer and souvenir stands, and the empty soundstages set up for street-party bands. Promoters had promised for weeks that the celebration, called The Big Dig, would be the biggest party <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> had ever seen. But <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> Shlenker </PERSON>, the man who will run the pyramid, said wet electronics made the affair too dangerous. Major events of The Big Dig included a fireworks display with a ton of explosives and a laser-light show outlining the shape of the 321-foot pyramid. Police said they had expected up to 100,000 spectators for the show but were unable to count the sparse crowd that showed up because it was too scattered through downtown. `` We're going to have the whole show tomorrow night,'' <PERSON> Shlenker </PERSON> said. `` It just got to a point tonight that the decision got taken out of our hands. It rained so hard that we've got pools of water. It's just too dangerous with the electrical equipment to risk peoples' lives.'' A late-night rock' n' roll concert featuring comedian <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Aykroyd </PERSON> and his <ORGANIZATION> Blues </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION> was to go on as scheduled at an amphitheater on the city's <LOCATION> Mud </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> tourist park near the pyramid site. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, who helped usher in rock' n' roll with his TV show `` American Bandstand,'' said the museum will be a hall of fame linked to his annual American Music Awards. The museum will include computerized displays with recordings and videotapes of the nation's musical past `` You'll be able to punch up a date and find out what musically was happening, what world events were happening and what it meant to your life,'' <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said. The concrete and stainless steel pyramid is scheduled to open in May 1991. It is called `` The Great American Pyramid.''
