<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, anxious for money to launch the war on drugs, says he is ready to deal with <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Democrats seeking to expand the program by $ 2.2 billion now and enlarge it in the future. `` We're flexible in terms of the funding method,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said at a White House luncheon Friday. `` But I strongly believe we must return the integrated elements of this drug strategy which took more than six months to develop.'' His comment came as a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bipartisan task force came away from two hours of negotiations Friday with Republicans promising to present a fresh financing plan when talks resume Monday. Meanwhile, the Rev. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> select committee on narcotics the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> plan `` does not match the breadth of this social crisis'' and urged summit-style talks to draw up a new version. In the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, the Democratic plan to generate an additional $ 2.2 billion through a half-percent, across-the-board cut in federal programs remained part of a money bill for transportation programs awaiting final floor action. The administration opposes the idea, offered by <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, which would slice $ 1.8 billion from the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s `` We ca n't afford to sacrifice our military preparedness,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said Friday. Democrats were confident following the initial session of the task force made up of nine <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> and nine Democratic senators. `` It was a good step,'' <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> told a news conference. Democrats said, however, that money agreements reached now would be only a start on the drug war and that they have fundamental disagreements with the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration over what its size and scale should be. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, D-Del., said Democrats eventually want to expand the attack on cocaine dealers beyond what has been envisioned thus far by Republicans and provide more treatment and education National drug policy director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, author of the drug plan, says it most likely will be expanded in the future and an updated version is due in February. He also says the administration's request is a sharp increase over a drug-fighting budget that was only $ 2 billion three years ago. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> drew applause and scattered shouts of approval from spectators as he told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> select committee on narcotics the nation needs `` a new initiative equal to the scope and depth of the problem.'' He criticized the plan for lack of enforcement strength, aid for the poor and input from national and community leaders with experience in fighting drugs. He said a meeting at the Camp David presidential retreat should be convened to redraw the strategy. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was sharply critical of both <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> and the president. `` In April, Mr. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> announced that he would take comprehensive emergency action to attack the drug crisis in the nation's capital,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. `` Five months later, we still have the emergency but no action.'' `` President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> announced a drug plan for <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. Where is his plan for the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> and cities around the nation?'' he said. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, reported to be weighing a race for mayor of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, suggested the nation's capital could be a model for fighting the drug scourge. He was asked what his role in that effort would be. `` A volunteer,'' he said.
