<HEAD>NASA Gets Go-Ahead For Controversial Probe Launch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> has White House approval to proceed with its much-debated October launch of a nuclear-powered satellite to <LOCATION> Jupiter </LOCATION>. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s science adviser, <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bromley </PERSON>, signed the authorization Friday which is required before a nuclear device is put into space. <PERSON> Bromley </PERSON> had the president's approval, said <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Alixe </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Truly </PERSON> was informed, she said. The mission would have been scrubbed had White House approval been withheld. Critics worried about nuclear fallout in case of an accident will ask a court to stop the launch, and promise to try to put their bodies in the way if that does n't work. The Galileo probe will be sent on its eight-year, $ 1.4 billion mission from the cargo bay of the space shuttle <LOCATION> Atlantis </LOCATION> _ the first time nuclear power has been carried on a shuttle. The three men and two women who will be on the Oct. 12 mission were in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> today for a breakfast with Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> at his residence. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, who intends to be at the Kennedy Space Center for the liftoff, heads the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> and was particularly interested in meeting the astronauts because shuttle commander <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> is from <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s home state. Protesters claim a Challenger-like accident could poison Earth's atmosphere with `` the most toxic substance in the universe. They are preparing to file suit in federal court to stop the mission and a protest march is scheduled to begin at <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canaveral </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION> on Sunday. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Gagnon </PERSON>, a leader in the <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION>, said `` we are going to attempt to enter the launch area and sit on the launch pad.'' He has written that `` Plutonium 238 is the most toxic substance in the universe. If ingested, it concentrates in the bone marrow where it can cause leukemia. If inhaled, it sticks to the lungs, where it can lead to cancer.'' The Galileo spacecraft was originally scheduled for launch in January 1982 but was delayed time and again. It is outfitted with two radioisotope thermoelectric generators to produce the electricity for the spacecraft, science instruments and engineering support systems. Of the 22 <ORGANIZATION> RTGs </ORGANIZATION> used on previous missions, three have been involved in accidents _ one releasing 17,000 curies of radioactive material 75 miles high over the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>. The generators use the heat from the radioactive decay of plutonium-238 dioxide to generate electricity. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> estimates the probability of having a launch accident that results in the release of plutonium into the atmosphere is one in 2,800. RTGs similar to the ones on Galileo provided the power for Voyager 2, which recently sent back spectacular views of the planet <LOCATION> Neptune </LOCATION>. Voyager 2, launched in 1977, was the last spacecraft carrying a nuclear power source.
