<HEAD>US Urges Other Nations to Take in Soviet Refugees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is calling on other nations to ease the burden on the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> by taking in some of the recent surge of emigres from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Deputy Secretary of State <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> issued the call Friday as he defended the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration from criticism that a proposal to allow 50,000 Soviet refugees into the country in the next year is too conservative. `` I resent the implication that we have some heartless, niggardly, conservative approach to this problem,'' <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on immigration. `` But there are limits on the numbers we can take,'' he said, citing budgetary constraints and the press of refugees worldwide seeking to come to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` No budget deficit, however large, should ever induce the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to abandon or compromise in any way its fundamental values and principles'' of granting safe haven to `` oppressed peoples,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Orrin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Utah </LOCATION>. Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., chairman of the subcommittee, said the months of administration deliberations on its Soviet refugees strategy had given the impression that `` you're dealing with cans of beans rather than human beings. Some 150,000 applications for entry _ mostly from Jews and some Pentacostals _ are expected in the 1990 fiscal year. Critics say that leaves the administration's quota figure too low. For nearly 20 years the demand for liberalized Soviet emigration was a cornerstone of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy, but `` never was it said that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> has an obligation to take them all in'' if the gates open, <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> said. He said <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> should also offer entry to the Soviets, although he conceded attempts to enlist the other countries' help over the past few months had not borne fruit. `` I ca n't tell you there will be a massive willingness on the part of other countries,'' he said, `` but we'll continue trying.'' Under existing procedures, most Soviet emigres leave the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> with <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> visas but change course for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> once they reach processing centers in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>. Only about 10 percent to 15 percent go to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. To save money, the administration will shut down the <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> facilities once it clears up the backlog of an estimated 30,000 applicants there, and process all applicants in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> after Oct. 1, <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> said.
