<HEAD>Author Robert Penn Warren Dead At 84</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STRATTON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Penn </PERSON> <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>, who won the Pulitzer Prize three times for his novels and poetry and was named the nation's first poet laureate, has died after a three-year battle with cancer. <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>, 84, died early Friday at his summer home. His wife, the author <PERSON> Eleanor </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, and a local doctor were with him, said <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, his longtime friend and <PERSON> Stratton </PERSON>'s town clerk and treasurer. Services will be private, with a public memorial service scheduled later, said a spokesman for the Covey and <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> Funeral Home in <LOCATION> Wilmington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> was the first to win Pulitzer Prizes in both poetry and fiction. The poetry prizes came in 1957 for `` Promises: Poems 1954-1956,'' and in 1979 for `` Now and Then: Poems 1976-1978.'' His novel `` All the King's Men,'' a book about the myth surrounding <PERSON> Huey </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON>, the swaggering populist governor of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, won the Pulitzer in 1947 and became an Academy Award-winning motion picture. His other awards include the Presidential Medal of Freedom, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Literature </ORGANIZATION> and the Gold Medal for Poetry from the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> and Letters. He also was among the first recipients of the <ORGANIZATION> MacArthur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>'s unrestricted `` genius grants. <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> was remembered as a brilliant poet, fiction writer, teacher and critic _ and as a nice man. `` He had such vigor and such love of life. He was such wonderful company _ he was the soul of hilarity,'' said novelist and short story writer <PERSON> Eudora </PERSON> <PERSON> Welty </PERSON>, whose first work was published in the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION> when <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> was editor in the 1930s. `` He was a good friend to writers _ constantly generous and giving.'' `` He was reticent, ironic, reserved and perfectly charming, and I loved and respected him quite apart from his work,'' said poet <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nemerov </PERSON>, who owns a copy of the first edition of <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>'s first book His fellow writers marveled at his versatility and virtuosity. `` He's astounding,'' said poet <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bly </PERSON>. `` It's very seldom that someone can write poetry and fiction and do it well. In fiction, you take nine or ten generations and compress them; in poetry, you take 30 seconds and expand it.'' Born in <LOCATION> Guthrie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, on April 24, 1905, <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> grew up hearing tales of the Civil War from his two grandfathers who had been Confederate soldiers. <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> graduated summa cum laude from <ORGANIZATION> Vanderbilt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in 1925, received a master's degree from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION> and studied at <ORGANIZATION> Oxford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> as a Rhodes Scholar. While teaching at <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, he was a founder of <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION>. From 1938 to 1961, he was an editorial adviser to the <ORGANIZATION> Kenyon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION>. His first full-length novel, published in 1939, was `` Night Rider,'' about the plight of <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> tobacco growers at the turn of the century. Other works included `` At Heaven's Gate,'' `` World Enough and Time,'' `` Band of Angels,'' `` Wilderness: A Tale of the Civil War,'' and `` Flood: A Romance for Our Time.'' In 1986, <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> was appointed poet laureate, a largely ceremonial title created by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` The people who create these posts do n't give a damn about poetry,'' <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> said of the appointment. `` They do it because it's a nice thing to do They think ` There's a poet down the road; let's make him a poet laureate.' <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> lived the last three decades of his life in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. Before his second marriage, to Ms. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, she had suggested that they return to the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> so that their children would know his world. `` But I discovered it was n't the same world,'' <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> once said. `` I had been carrying a dream around in my head.''
