<HEAD>Exxon Halts Spill Cleanup, Governor Praises `Good-Faith Effort'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 On a sun-drenched day, <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> pulled out its cleanup crews for the winter and the state announced its own plan to protect fish hatcheries and untainted areas from the Exxon Valdez oil spill. `` It's a nice day for the first day of winter, is n't it?'' Gov. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> said Friday before he announced the state's plans for a $ 21 million program `` to continue cleanup work left by <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>.'' But for that bit of sarcasm, and a crack by his spokesman about a `` dirty dozen of soiled beaches'' left by <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> was conciliatory toward the oil company responsible for the March 24 tanker wreck that left 10.9 million gallons of crude oil in Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>. The governor thanked the thousands of workers who helped scrub the oil-fouled shorelines, proclaiming Friday `` Oil Spill Workers Appreciation Day'' in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> pulled the crews out Friday, saying <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s early winter makes continuing field work too risky. `` I think Exxon has made a good-faith effort to clean up the beaches,'' <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> said. `` I'm not going to fault Exxon here. They made some mistakes and, frankly, some of the things the state has done were mistakes.'' <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> said the state should have known how to clean up a major spill. `` At least we should have known no one else knew how to do it,'' he said. <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s winter program, announced on a warm fall day when residents donned T-shirts and shorts, calls for: _ Small-scale cleanups when fish and wildlife resources are threatened by the remaining oil _ Monitoring the oil's movement and changes in its composition during the region's severe winter months _ Research and development of new ways to remove the remaining oil, most of which lies under the surface of rocky shorelines _ Protecting the region's five fish hatcheries with standby equipment and crews _ Forming a strike force of counselors and mental-health professionals to help prevent and treat stress-related problems, such as drug and alcohol abuse, in spill-affected towns Money for the program will come from the state's new 5-cent-a-barrel oil-spill response tax. <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> eventually will be billed for reimbursement. While <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> had little negative to say about <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>, he showed reporters a seven-minute, state-produced video that focused on the oiled shores the company has vacated. On a nearby table were oiled rocks taken this week from what a Cowper spokesman said were soiled beaches. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Beathard </PERSON> said later that the beaches where surface oil remains visible were the last treated with a chemical fertilizer. The fertilizer, which stimulates the oil-eating action of microorganisms, takes up to six weeks to work. State environmental officials are worried about the subsurface oil. They fear winter storms and tidal action will loosen that oil, resulting in small slicks that will pollute other areas. Although <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> has promised to monitor the oil and respond to emergencies during the fall and winter, <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> said it remained unclear to what extent the company will work with the state. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> has said it will re-evaluate the shorelines next spring and decide then whether to resume the cleanup on a large scale. The governor noted that some biologists alleged recently that <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s cleanup, which employed as many as 12,000 workers, may have done more environmental harm than good. `` That may be,'' <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> said. `` But what was Exxon going to do? Not only was everyone barking at them to get it done, including us, they had a public relations problem.''
