<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A strong earthquake rocked the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Caspian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> area early today, cracking some buildings but apparently causing no serious damage or injuries, seismologists reported The quake occurred at 6:05 a.m. and was centered in the <LOCATION> Caspian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> about 110 miles east of <LOCATION> Baku </LOCATION>, the capital of <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Nadezhda </PERSON> <PERSON> Molchanova </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <LOCATION> Obninsk </LOCATION> Seismic Station near <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. The Caspian Sea separates the <LOCATION> Caucasus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> region and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, two active seismic areas. A powerful quake Dec. 7 in western <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, about 370 miles west of today's quake, killed 25,000 people. Monitors at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Earthquake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Golden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, measured the quake at 6.6 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale. The Armenian earthquake registered 6.9 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale, a gauge of the energy released by a temblor, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a seismograph. A quake measuring 6 can cause severe damage and a temblor measuring 7 can cause widespread, heavy damage. Ms. <PERSON> Molchanova </PERSON> said there were no immediate reports of casualties. She said the quake registered 7 on the Soviet earthquake scale in <LOCATION> Krasnovodsk </LOCATION>, a city on the eastern shore of the <LOCATION> Caspian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Turkmenia </LOCATION>. The Soviet scale is based on observable effects of an earthquake. A quake registering 7 is regarded as `` very strong,'' capable of making cracks in stone walls. It registered at 5 in <LOCATION> Baku </LOCATION>, strong enough to wake the sleeping and shake furniture.
