ested were hired killers sent by Colombian drug traffickers to murder <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> or Canadian officials or to attack President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s vacation home in <LOCATION> Kennebunkport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> late Friday, <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Vezeris </PERSON> said, `` We do not believe it has anything to do with threats to individuals in this country.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has sent <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> $ 65 million in aid, including military equipment, for its month-old crackdown on the nation's drug cartels, which provide most of the cocaine sold in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Canadian and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> officials say the cartels increasingly are smuggling drugs through <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s maritime provinces because the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has tightened its borders. When Mounted Police and <LOCATION> Edmundston </LOCATION> authorities arrested four of the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> men, a search of their vehicles uncovered an Uzi submachine gun, Soviet and Israeli assault rifles and 3,000 rounds of ammunition. Also seized were six automatic pistols, a .22 - caliber pistol, tear gas, a deactivated Japanese grenade and an electric zap gun used to knock people On Friday, police led the four handcuffed into a heavily guarded provincial court in <LOCATION> Edmundston </LOCATION>, where they were charged with a variety of weapons offenses. `` Innocent, innocent. Je suis innocent,'' one of the men told reporters outside the courthouse. `` No speak English,'' said another. Authorities have identified the four as <PERSON> Tito </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON>, <PERSON> Euovio </PERSON> <PERSON> Man