<FIRST>r a PM-DC-10-Safety Bjt   09-16 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-10-Safety, Bjt,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Modifications to Be Made on DC-10s Following Iowa Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> says it will make changes in its DC-10 jetliners to guard against failure of all three hydraulic systems, the `` one in a billion'' condition in a DC-10 crash in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> that killed 112 people. The modifications were greeted warmly Friday by <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Busey </PERSON>, the head of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. `` The system design changes proposed by <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> ... are a solid step forward in assuring there will be no repeat of the July 19 accident,'' <PERSON> Busey </PERSON> said in a statement issued in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> `` Once these design changes are in place, they will raise the already high safety standards required of the DC-10 and, in effect, make a good airplane even better.'' The three hydraulic systems on the DC-10 are designed to operate independently and to back each other up in case one fails. Unlike some other plane models, the 400 or so DC-10s in use around the world have no backup system if the hydraulic lines fail to control the wing and tail mechanisms that steer the plane. `` We view the new enhancements as extra safety equipment similar to the installation of air bags in automobiles _ additional measures to protect occupants besides the lap belts, shoulder harnesses, padded dashboards, etc.,'' said <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>, a vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>, who headed the company's investigation of the <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, crash, said Friday modifications will include: _ An electrically operated shutoff valve that will be installed in the supply line and a check valve in the return line of the 3 hydraulic system. _ A check valve installed in the No 3 hydraulic reservoir. _ A cockpit light added to alert the crew if the shutoff valve is activated The new fast-acting shutoff valve, located just behind the back wall of the cabin, will close automatically and the cockpit light will come on if a sensor detects hydraulic fluid dropping below a preset level in the reservoir. Even if all three hydraulic systems are affected by severe damage to the tail section, as happened in <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, the valve will stop fluid flow through the No. 3 system, <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> said. With adequate hydraulic pressure preserved in that system, the crew should have enough control to fly the plane to a safe landing, he said. In the July crash, the tail engine on the DC-10 disintegrated, knocking out all three hydraulic systems _ an event with a `` one in a billion'' chance of occurring, according to a <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> release Friday. The pilot lost virtually all control of the plane, which exploded in flames in a corn field after cartwheeling down the runway. <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a division of <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> based in <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, manufactured the DC-10s, which will eventually be replaced by the more advanced but similar MD-11s. <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Elayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Bendel </PERSON> said in a telephone interview that the company had yet to decide whether to make the same modifications to its MD-11s.
</TEXT>
