<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NYNEX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and its striking workers broke off contract talks early this morning after a day of on-again, off-again negotiations to end the six-week strike. `` Nothing was resolved, and no more negotiating sessions have been scheduled,'' said <PERSON> Adele </PERSON> <PERSON> Stacy </PERSON> of Local 2222 of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brotherhood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electrical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION>. Negotiators for the telephone company and the <ORGANIZATION> IBEW </ORGANIZATION> met intermittently Friday morning and afternoon, and union leaders said the company appeared to be pushing to reach a settlement by midnight. But the talks at <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s Park Plaza Hotel ended fruitlessly at 12:25 a.m. Earlier in the day, ebullient union leaders addressing 700 strikers at a rally outside <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s headquarters in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> said the six-week strike had been significantly strengthened by a <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> ruling that the workers would be entitled to unemployment benefits starting next week. <PERSON> Myles </PERSON> <PERSON> Calvey </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brotherhood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electrical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Local </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> 2222 </ORGANIZATION>, estimated that unemployment payments for 12,000 <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> workers would cost the telephone company $ 9 million per week. <PERSON> Calvey </PERSON> and <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Early </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Communications </OR