<HEAD>Blowtorch May Have Triggered Explosion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MORGANFIELD, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Investigators suspect that a blowtorch probably caused an explosion that killed 10 miners, but the probe has been delayed while dangerous levels of methane are cleared from the mine, authorities said. State inspectors found the blowtorch Friday near the site of Wednesday's explosion, which officials believe to have been fueled by methane gas, said <PERSON> Willard </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON>, commissioner of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minerals </ORGANIZATION>. Workers may have been using the torch to disassemble a longwall mining, investigators said. Officials of the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Mine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> approved a modified company plan to reduce the methane levels at the <LOCATION> William </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION> mine that delayed the investigation Friday, said administration spokeswoman <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON>. <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> said one of the mine's curtains _ used to channel outside air to mining areas to carry away methane gas _ appeared to be dislodged. <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> said he did n't know if the curtain was moved out of place before the blast, by the explosion itself or during rescue operations. On Friday night, hours after the first burial of the mine disaster, scores of area residents gathered for a memorial service at <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. `` In <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, our families are strong. Our communities are supportive, and our courage is abundant,'' Gov. <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON> told the crowd