<HEAD>At Least 14 Killed In Slide</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MLA1,2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Monsoon rains loosened earth in a quarry in a <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> suburb, triggering a landslide today that buried more than a dozen houses in a nearby squatter colony. At least 14 people were killed, officials said. <PERSON> Zenaida </PERSON> <PERSON> Santa </PERSON> <PERSON> Ana </PERSON>, head social worker of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Welfare </ORGANIZATION> and Development for the <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> area, said the landslide occurred at 6:00 a.m. in the village of <LOCATION> Tunasan </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Muntinglupa </LOCATION>, just south of the capital. Ms. <PERSON> Santa </PERSON> <PERSON> Ana </PERSON> said soldiers, police officers and civilian volunteers dug up 14 bodies under the tons of mud, rock and debris. Seven of the eight people found alive were in serious condition, she said. The landslide destroyed at least 14 shanties. Ms. <PERSON> Santa </PERSON> <PERSON> Ana </PERSON> said 68 families living near the quarry were evacuated to a nearby chapel because of fears that additional rain may trigger another landslide. Ten hours after the incident, rescuers still were searching for one male resident of the area, she said. She said the rescue had been slow because the area is an interior village and is not accessible to large digging equipment. Most rescuers were using using their hands, picks, shovels and pails.
