<HEAD>Governor Signs Bill Lowering Allowable Drinking Limit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to restore time element, clarify that ceremony
was to enact bill; picks up 4th graf, ``He said...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON> enacted one of the strictest drunken driving laws in the country, lowering the blood alcohol level at which a person is presumed too drunk to drive to 0.08 percent. The bill, lowering the unacceptable blood alcohol level from 0.10 percent, will take effect next Jan. 1. Only three other states _ <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> _ have as tough a standard. `` This is a very strong signal and message to individuals who do drink and do drive that it is more likely that they will wind up being convicted of drunken driving, and hopefully this will be a very strong incentive to prevent them from doing so,'' <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON> told an audience of news reporters and uniformed law enforcement officers at a signing ceremony Friday in his office. He said drunken driving deaths had decreased on <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> highways in recent years, but were still too high to accept. `` I am convinced we are going to save lives under this bill,'' said <PERSON> Assemblyman </PERSON> <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON>, author of the new law. `` I do n't want anyone arrested under this bill. I want people who drink to stay off the road. It's a health problem. It's a criminal problem.'' Although each individual's blood alcohol level is affected by a variety of factors, such as weight, the average person can consume about three glasses of beer or comparable amounts of other alcholic beverages in an hour before reaching the 0.08 percent level.
