<HEAD>Arab League Committee Calls For Immediate Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JIDDAH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A three-man peacemaking committee called for an `` immediate and comprehensive'' cease-fire in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> today as a first step in a settlement of the 14-year-old civil war. In a communique issued in <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>, whose foreign ministers make up the committee, the three countries said that `` there can be no solution to the <LOCATION> Lebanese </LOCATION> crisis by military means.'' The cease-fire call was meant to `` spare the bloodletting, and to spread security and stability and provide the propitious atmosphere for national reconciliation.'' The cease-fire demand was the first point in a seven-point peace plan contained in the communique. A Lebanese security body to be headed by <PERSON> Lakhdar </PERSON> <PERSON> Ibrahimi </PERSON>, an Algerian who is the committee's delegate to <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, would supervise the implementation of the cease-fire, the committee said. It would also supervise ships `` when information is received by the committee that they are carrying arms and ammunition to any party.'' As soon as the security body began its work, the naval blockade would be lifted and <ORGANIZATION> Beirut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airport </ORGANIZATION> reopened, the communique said. It asked all the belligerents in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> to `` immediately cease the use of arms by all means, whichever the party.'' It called on all concerned states, and those who supported the committee in its task, `` to work by all means to halt the flow of arms to any one in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>.'' The committee invited the members of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> to meet to prepare and discuss a `` charter for national reconciliation'' on Sept. 30 after the cease-fire has been stabilized, the naval blockade lifted and the airport reopened. The venue of the meeting would be declared after consultations by <PERSON> Ibrahimi </PERSON>, the communique said. Ibrahimi would be heading to <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> on Sunday to put the decisions into effect, the communique added.
