<HEAD>Teacher Strike Wrenching in Montana City</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Kenczka, chairman...', to CORRECT governor's
name to Stan sted Dan Stephens.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM LACEKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREAT FALLS, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 She stood in the gutter outside C.M. <ORGANIZATION> Russell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in the chill morning sun of early fall, hugging her craggy-faced biology teacher _ and crying for him. `` My teachers are my friends, and I support them,'' said 15-year-old <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Gillin </PERSON>. Teacher <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenczka </PERSON>, the morning picket captain for strikers at the school, is one of about 700 of the city's 720 teachers who have been strike since Aug. 27. More than 500 substitutes have filled in since classes began Sept. 5. `` I do n't think this will end until they -LRB- the school board -RRB- see these kids as we see them,'' said <PERSON> Kenczka </PERSON>, who returned the girl's hug <PERSON> Kenczka </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Russell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> biology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> department </ORGANIZATION> last year, has been a teacher for 34 years. <PERSON> Ann </PERSON>, the granddaughter of <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>'s Republican Gov <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON>, refused to attend a substitute's class, declaring to her parents that she would honor the picket line The strike in this prairie city about 70 miles northwest of <PERSON> Helena </PERSON>, the capital, has sharply divided the community's 60,000 residents. The only previous teachers strike in <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION> was in 1975. `` Standing out here and watching somebody walk past you into your classroom is like standing in your driveway and watching somebody sleep in your bed,'' said <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON>, a fourth-grade teacher at <LOCATION> Riverview </LOCATION> Elementary who declined to give her full name. The school board and the <ORGANIZATION> Great </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Falls </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> remain in disagreement over about 20 issues, including salaries, insurance and transfer policy. Talks are continuing, haltingly. Frustration on all sides _ teachers, administrators, students, parents _ is building into anger. <ORGANIZATION> Outside </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Great </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Falls </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, one of the city's two high schools, teachers shouted `` Scab! Scab!'' recently at substitutes filing into the school. Some of the substitutes instinctively hunched their shoulders as they passed the gantlet of strikers. Later, inside the high school, one of the substitutes called the harassment `` terrorism.'' But most were quiet about their situation, saying they did n't have time for an interview during school hours. None of the substitute teachers took up invitations to talk later. At <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION> <LOCATION> High </LOCATION>, female pupils repeatedly came to hug striking teachers, and some cried. Grim-faced boys offered encouragement and complained that the substitutes were incompetent. But many students who entered the school _ attendance has increased gradually to more than 70 percent _ averted their eyes and did not speak as they walked past the teachers. `` A lot of these kids need hugs,'' said <PERSON> Karol </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, principal at Great Falls High. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said she feels caught in the middle. She makes a point of stopping to talk with the strikers each day. `` There are some of my staff who will have a hard time forgiving me for that,'' she said. She helped negotiate the last three contracts, but declined to get involved in the prickly talks this year. Recently, though, she joined four secondary principals in sending a letter to the superintendent urging a settlement. `` I want my staff back,'' she said. `` The subs are working hard, but they are substitutes.'' At <LOCATION> Riverview </LOCATION>, the mood was calmer. The strikers have a barbecue grill in the parking lot. The young children often come to them at recess to ask when they will come back, the teachers said. The teachers said it's hard explaining contracts to kindergarteners. But, they said, the children understand the word `` fair.''
