<HEAD>Troops on Alert On Love and Friendship Day; Two Police Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with shooting in Bogota, troops on patrol
in major cities, air force reminder of policy to down suspicious planes.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soldiers patrolled city streets today and the air force reiterated orders to force down suspicious aircraft following drug-related violence that killed two policemen on the eve of a holiday celebrating love and friendship. As the nation observed the Day of Love and Friendship, army soldiers on foot and in jeeps roamed <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Cali </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Barranquilla </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s four biggest cities. On Friday, gunmen firing from a speeding car killed two police officers in <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>, police reported. Later Friday, assailants also in a speeding car opened fire at the daily newspaper <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Siglo </ORGANIZATION>, police said. No one was injured in that attack. In the cocaine capital of <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION>, two policemen were wounded when a bomb exploded near a police truck Friday. And in <LOCATION> Cali </LOCATION>, home of another major cocaine cartel, three bombs wounded two policemen and seven civilians, police said. They said another bomb found at a bus station was deactived. No one claimed responsibility for the attacks, but suspicion fell on the nation's drug lords, who have been at war for a month with the government. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> put the country's 200,000-man army and 80,000 national police on alert, canceling all leaves and keeping the forces on standby. <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> police chief <PERSON> Nasin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gianini </PERSON> <PERSON> Diaz </PERSON> said reports of `` telephone terrorism,'' in which callers make bomb and death threats, increased in the capital on the eve of today's national holiday, during which Colombians exchange gifts. `` Citizens should take the threats seriously and report them to police,'' he said in an interview on Colombian television. `` But we are guaranteeing a peaceful Day of Love and Friendship.'' Armored trucks and army troops were sent to guard banks and government buildings. Banks are frequent targets of the nation's powerful cocaine traffickers. They have declared `` total and absolute war'' on the government, which began a crackdown on trafficking after a leading presidential candidate, Sen. <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Galan </PERSON>, was assassinated Aug. 18. As part of its effort to combat drug trafficking, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s air force issued orders 12 years ago for its pilots to force down civilian planes that do not have permission to fly over <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. The air force commander, Gen. <PERSON> Alfonso </PERSON> <PERSON> Amaya </PERSON>, sent a copy of the orders to the civil aeronautics agency Friday as a reminder of the policy. The air force has forced down dozens of planes without flight plans in the past 12 years but never has resorted to shooting down a plane. Under emergency powers decreed by President <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barco </PERSON>, authorities have confiscated hundreds of properties allegedly belonging to drug kingpins and pledged to extradite drug suspects wanted in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. So far, one person has been extradited, <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> <PERSON> Romero </PERSON>, an alleged whiz financier for the <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> cartel. He was flown to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> Sept. 6, where he is to stand trial on money laundering charges. Two other drug suspects are being held in a maximum security prison pending extradition to <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> and to <LOCATION> Tallahassee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s top cocaine barons have escaped capture, however In the <LOCATION> Canadian </LOCATION> province of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION> Friday, authorities said they had linked five men arrested with an arsenal of weapons to two Colombians accused of importing drugs into that country. The five men were carrying Venezuelan passports and were arrested in <LOCATION> Edmundston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION>, on Wednesday and Thursday. The Colombians, <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Galindo-Escobar </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Mendoza-Jaramillo </PERSON>, Thursday were ordered held for trial in <LOCATION> Fredericton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION> next month on charges of importing 1,100 pounds of cocaine.
