<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill, Bjt,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Environmentalists Not Happy With House Bill Nearing Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As Exxon suspends its <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> oil cleanup for the winter amid sharp criticism from environmentalists, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is nearing a vote that critics say could limit how much oil companies would have to pay for major spills. Earlier this year, environmentalists applauded approval by a 99-0 vote in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> of legislation that would impose unlimited liability against a shipper responsible for an oil spill and a $ 1 billion oil industry cleanup fund. But the House version of the bill, which is expected to come to a vote this week, has prompted a letter-writing campaign from a dozen environmental groups who say the measure would reduce, not strengthen, protection against oil spills and weaken cleanup requirements. `` This is an industry bailout bill,'' snapped <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Frampton </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Wilderness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. `` It weakens current oil spill law and caters to the oil industry,'' charged <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardiner </PERSON>, legislative director of the <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bills would have to be reconciled before final legislation is approved by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. In the weeks after the Exxon Valdez tanker fouled hundreds of miles of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s pristine shoreline last March, members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> clamored to sign onto proposals aimed at making sure industry prepares better for future spills and that federal law more clearly spells out a polluter's liability. But the legislation that has actually emerged from two <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committees _ both often friendly to oil and shipping interests _ contains provisions the environmentalists say fall far short of those rhetorical clamors. Oil industry spokesmen have supported the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> legislation and point out that _ like the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> version _ it would establish for the first time a $ 1 billion industry fund to deal with cleanup efforts. The fund would come from a surcharge on each barrel of oil. Environmentalists argue this would simply pass costs on to the consumer and provide no incentive for companies to take precautions against oil spills. The environmental groups, ranging from the 5.8 million-member <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> to the relatively small <ORGANIZATION> Izaak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Walton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>, are alarmed about provisions in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> legislation that would: _ Put a cap, possibly as low as $ 60 million, on a shipper's direct liability for a spill Such a level dwarfs the already acknowledged $ 1 billion to $ 2 billion cleanup costs being talked about from the Exxon spill. _ Override stronger oil spill liability laws in effect in 18 states. These state laws have no liability ceiling and allow civil suits for damages against the oil companies involved in a spill. _ Allow for a narrow definition in calculating the value of a natural resource such as wildlife, fish and birds. Such calculations would let an oil company off the hook by not making them pay for long-term restoration of such resources, conservationists charge. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, the oil industry trade organization, has argued that unlimited direct liability for a spill makes it difficult to obtain insurance and that the various state laws foster the filing of too many lawsuits. The industry has sought a federal liability law that would preempt state laws for years, but each time has been unsuccessful. Rep. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.C. </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Merchant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fisheries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and one of the sponsors of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bill, disputes claims that the oil companies would benefit by the legislation. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>' committee approved the bill by a voice vote last Thursday. Committee staffers point out that a shipper would still be directly liable for cleanup costs beyond the ceiling established by the bill if gross negligence can be shown and the oil industry still would have to pay for up to $ 1 billion in cleanup costs, albeit through the special fund fueled by surcharges. Environmentalists maintain that the catch is in proving gross negligence on the part of a corporation _ as opposed to an individual that might work for the corporation. A floor vote is expected on the bill by midweek and environmentalists are hoping amendments to be offered by Reps. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Calif </LOCATION>., and <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Studds </PERSON>, D-Mass., will bring it more closely in line with the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> `` This will show which representatives sides with big oil and which takes the side of environmental protection,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Maddy </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voters </ORGANIZATION>.
