<SECOND>AM-NYC Mayoral, Bjt,0734</SECOND>
<HEAD>After Koch: A Clash of Quieter Styles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One dresses like an undertaker and talks like a diplomat; the other more resembles an ex-altar boy. Neither even remotely takes after <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>, the city's celebrated, reviled and garrulous mayor since 1977. But one of them will take his job. The altar boy is <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON>, winner of last week's Republican mayoral primary His opponent is <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON>, who toppled <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> in the Democratic contest with surprising ease. Whoever wins the general election, political analysts say the two mark a new era of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> politics. <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> is the first Republican in 25 years with a shot at City Hall. <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON> would be the first black mayor. `` In a thematic way, New Yorkers are looking for change. The voting in both primaries suggested that,'' said <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Harding </PERSON>, chief of the city's tiny <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, whose nomination <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> also holds. `` In the general election, change is the paramount issue.'' <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> hopes so. He is the ultimate political outsider, a Republican in an overwhelmingly Democratic city, a former federal prosecutor who made his name chasing corruption in city government and <LOCATION> Wall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION>, a man who never has held elective office. `` <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON>'s principal asset is that he has no background in government. Therefore he can say he's going to change things,'' said <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> <PERSON> Moss </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` He can take the full offense: He says, ` I'll clean house.''' True to form, in accepting the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> nomination Tuesday night, <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> described his campaign as a `` crusade'' to establish `` a new generation of leadership in this city.'' The next day he personalized the attack, calling <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON> a `` clubhouse politician'' tied to a discredited Democratic regime. Still, <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON>, 45, faces formidable odds. Two-thirds of the city's 3 million registered voters are Democrats. It took just 75,000 Republican votes for <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> to overwhelm his primary opponent, cosmetics heir <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauder </PERSON>; <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON>, to defeat <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> and two other Democrats, got nearly 540,000 votes. `` This is a Democratic town with a vengeance,'' said <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Adler </PERSON>, a veteran political consultant. `` You've got to get a whole lot of Democrats to vote for you if you want to win.'' <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON>, 62, has promptly seized that advantage, making party affiliation a prime issue. `` <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> will not become a Republican beachhead in 1989,'' he declared Wednesday at a rally with his defeated opponents. He personalized his attack as well, characterizing <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> as an agent of `` reactionary Republican government.'' The two are likely to tangle on other issues, including legal abortion, which <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON> supports and <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> has addressed equivocally; the death penalty, which <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> supports and <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON> opposes; and drugs and crime, on which <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON> seeks to counter <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON>'s crimefighting image. But neither is a Koch, whose acid tongue created issues as often as it addressed them. <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON>'s first words Tuesday night were to congratulate <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON> and pledge `` a race that unites <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>.'' And <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON> called himself `` the guy that brings people together.'' The prime challenge for <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> borough president, is to bring even more voters together than he did in the primary. He won nine in 10 black voters, half the Hispanics and roughly three in 10 whites, mainly the young and the liberal. But he lost <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, the boroughs with the largest white populations. `` The same people who said <PERSON> David </PERSON> could n't win the primary for any number of reasons _ too black, too <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, too liberal _ now will say the same thing about his race against <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Adler </PERSON> said. But broadening his appeal was <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON>' byword in the primary. A career officeholder who served 10 years as city clerk, he is a formal, reserved and conciliatory figure, so reticent his critics call him indecisive. `` <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON>' principal asset is that he represents a new group whose time has come,'' <PERSON> Moss </PERSON> said. `` He provides an opportunity for blacks and <PERSON> Hispanics </PERSON> to take a major leadership role in municipal government.'' At the same time, he said, `` The challenge is for <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON> to disassociate himself from the perception that he's the candidate of one interest group. And to demonstrate that he's a black candidate, running for mayor, who is concerned with all people.''
