<HEAD>New Challenge For Pilots: Fly The Airline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dream of some pilots to buy their own planes and run an airline is becoming reality for 6,326 <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> flyers, who will have to learn to operate in the boardroom as well as the cockpit. The federal government, Wall Street analysts, aviation experts and employees of other airlines are watching closely the employee-management buyout of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>, approved last week by the airline's parent company, <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Some say it should make <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>'s advertised `` friendly skies'' even friendlier, but the $ 7.2 billion deal that would make <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> the nation's largest employee-owned company still faces some obstacles and raises some scepticism. It wo n't be the first time a pilot has owned an airline or moved in with management. But it will be the first time employees have taken a controlling interest in a major carrier. The pilots' share would be 75 percent, with 10 percent held by current management and 15 percent by <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>. The deal still faces potential hurdles, including participation of the machinists and flight attendants unions and approval by shareholders and the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION>. And despite <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> approval, a competing bid by <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> billionaire <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> still looms. On Friday, he offered to match the $ 300-per-share deal if the pilot's plan falls through. `` Pilots spend more time in the cockpit discussing how they'd run the airline than anything else,'' said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> pilot who joined management and now runs <ORGANIZATION> AVITAS </ORGANIZATION>, an aviation consulting firm. `` If anyone is cut out to run an airline, it's the pilots,'' he said, but added that does n't necessarily mean pilots will make the best managers for a complex company like <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>. Some of them tend to see little beyond the aircraft itself, he said. United pilots do n't intend to actually run the airline, but they will have a say in who does, and they expect some changes, including less acrimony between employees and management. The plan calls for <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> and chief financial officer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pope </PERSON> to continue running the company for the new employee-owners, said pilots spokesman <PERSON> Hank </PERSON> <PERSON> Krakowski </PERSON>. He predicted the deal will go through even without participation of machinists, flight attendants or the company's 26,000 nonunion employees. Negotiations are underway to include all 68,000 employees. Passengers might expect some changes, <PERSON> Krakowski </PERSON> said. Pilots are likely to announce over the plane's public address system that the owner is at the wheel, he said. `` I think you'll see pilots more inclined to walk back into the cabin and actually show an interest towards the customer,'' he said. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Joedicke </PERSON>, advisory director of the Wall Street firm of <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> could become `` more attractive from the aspect of service'' because employees who own the company are more likely to project a friendly image. He said the deal also should make <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> more competitive on fares because of the wage and work concessions. Aviation analyst <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Stockman </PERSON> said the arrangement should not make a difference in safety, because <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> already has a top maintenance record, but he said it should make a more harmonious company. `` They wo n't be arguing with management. They'll be arguing with themselves,'' he said. <PERSON> Stockman </PERSON> said, however, the arrangement raises doubts about the future of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which represents pilots, questioning whether pilot owners would want to stay in the powerful union. `` Why should they pay dues to protect the employees from themselves?'' he asked. `` We're in unchartered waters here.'' <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Daugherty </PERSON>, aviation analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, said the takeover could add to management problems. `` Management has a tough enough time. When you have different voices and groups with different interests involved, it could be even tougher to run the company,'' he said. But <PERSON> Daugherty </PERSON> added that ownership should give employees `` pretty intense interest in making sure the company comes out OK.''
