<HEAD>Northeastern Caribbean Awaits `Extremely Dangerous' Storm</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3-4th grafs, `At 9 a.m....', to UPDATE location, motion
speed. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `The storm's...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hurricane Hugo, the most powerful storm to hit the northeastern <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> in a decade, was bearing down on the <LOCATION> Leeward </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> today with 140 mph winds and a 10-foot wall of water. `` This is an extremely dangerous hurricane,'' hurricane specialist <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayfield </PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hurricane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in suburban <LOCATION> Coral </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gables </LOCATION> said. `` This is stonger than Hurricane <PERSON> David </PERSON> back in 1979,'' which left 1,200 dead in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. At noon EDT today, <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON>'s center near 15.6 north latitude and 59.0 west longitude, or about 175 miles east-southeast of the <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> resort island of <LOCATION> Guadeloupe </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Leeward </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>. It was expected to hit the island this afternoon or tonight, said forecaster <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, before moving in the direction of <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>. The hurricane was moving west at 14 mph, sending showers and gusty winds to the eastern edge of the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>. The storm's strength flucutated this morning, dipping from 150 mph at 6 a.m. to 140 mph at 9 a.m. It was expected to continue to do so as the size of the eye contracts and expands, forecasters said, but storm-force winds of 39 mph and above extend 150 miles from the center. In <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> France </ORGANIZATION> announced it was canceling all three of its flights scheduled today to <LOCATION> Martinique </LOCATION> because of the storm. Miami-based <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> planned no cancellations or reroutings today, but spokesman <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> said, `` We'll keep monitoring it very closely.'' Forecasters wo n't be able to tell for five or six days whether <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> will hit the coastal <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, forecaster <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Gross </PERSON> said. A hurricane warning was posted from <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lucia </LOCATION> north to <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Martin </LOCATION> including the <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virgin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>, and a hurricane watch the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virgin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> may be upgraded to a warning today. A tropical storm watch was in effect for the islands of <LOCATION> Barbados </LOCATION> and <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON>, according to the hurricane center. Forecasters classed the hurricane in Category 4, meaning it is considered capable of extreme damage. If its sustained winds grow to 155 mph, it would be classified in Category 5, capable of catastrophic damage. Only two Category 5 hurricanes have hit the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> since record-keeping began; the latest, <PERSON> Camille </PERSON> in 1969, killed 256 people. Islanders were warned to expect rainfall amounts of 5 to 10 inches and a storm surge with waves 10 feet higher than normal. <LOCATION> Dominica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guadeloupe </LOCATION>'s closest neighbor to the south, has only recently recovered from the destruction <PERSON> David </PERSON> wrought 10 years ago, when floods and mud slides poured down from mountains onto coastal towns and villages. On <LOCATION> Martinique </LOCATION>, the next island in the chain, school officials canceled classes today. A disaster response team from <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Metro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> established a communications center in <LOCATION> Barbados </LOCATION>, about 200 miles south of <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON>'s path, to assess damage and coordinate emergency medical treatment throughout the <LOCATION> Leeward </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>. At the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> station in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, guardsmen were preparing for the storm Friday. `` You go around and police the area and pick up anything that can become a missile hazard,'' Petty Officer <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Burd </PERSON> said. The island chain has escaped the worst of previous hurricanes this year. <PERSON> Dean </PERSON>, <PERSON> Erin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gabrielle </PERSON> turned north toward <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION> before reaching the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>. This time, there were no signs of the lowering atmospheric pressure that veered the others away. <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> is the eighth named storm of the current <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> hurricane season, which runs from June 1 to Nov. 30. Tropical storms have maximum sustained winds of 39 mph and reach hurricane status when winds reach 74 mph.
