<HEAD>Police Confiscate 7 Tons of Ivory; Arrest Six</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WDH2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police confiscated 980 elephant tusks weighing about seven tons Saturday and arrested six men suspected of running an international ivory smuggling operation. Police said the haul was one of the world's largest seizures of poached ivory. Police spokesman Kierie du Rand said the ivory would sell for about $ 1.5 million. Police discovered it when they stopped a truck at <LOCATION> Okahandja </LOCATION>, 45 miles north of <LOCATION> Windhoek </LOCATION>, he said. The tusks are believed to have come from elephants in southern <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and northern <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s elephant population has fallen from about 1.5 million in 1978 to as few as 400,000, due mostly to poachers who seek the valuable tusks. Several Western nations, including the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, recently have banned the import of ivory, and the 102-nation <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> in </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Endangered </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Species </ORGANIZATION> will consider a worldwide ban on the ivory trade next month. <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s 14-year-old civil war has made it virtually impossible to stop poaching in the southern part of the country. <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> allows a limited legal trade in ivory. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Botswana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> hold similar positions, saying properly managed ivory sales allow them to keep the elephant population under control and generate revenue for conservation programs.
