<FIRST>r w AM-PrecisionChoppers     09-16 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Precision Choppers,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0514 to correct cycle designator</HEAD>
<HEAD>US Team Wins Soviet Friends, Third International Crown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The 16 members of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> precision helicopter team eagerly swapped war stories and tie tacks with their Soviet competitors at the world helicopter championships, but struck out when they tried to trade car license plates. `` Some guys had these great license plates made up for the team, and wanted to trade, but none of the Soviets owned a car,'' recalled pilot <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Iseminger </PERSON> with a laugh. Iseminger and his co-pilot and navigator <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hobbs </PERSON> took the top individual honors at the competition, held last week outside <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. Both <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> warrant officers are helicopter instructors based at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rucker </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>. As part of the seven-team <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> contingent, they came away with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' third consecutive championship, and a lesson in the men they could possibly face off against should the superpowers ever go to war <PERSON> Hobbs </PERSON>, who admits to being dubbed `` Mushmouth'' by his comrades, acknowledged that when words failed, hand signals often made do. But the business of flying was n't topic No. 1. `` We exchanged war stories, and talked about our ways of life,'' <PERSON> Hobbs </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> after the competition. `` They did n't speak English very well, but they understood it better.'' Iseminger, who also was the pilot of the winning crew at the last world meet in 1986, said the Soviets `` were a lot more open, a lot more jovial and friendly'' than during previous years, an apparent reflection of Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s new policy of openess toward the West. However, the friendly communication had its limits. Although the military background of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> team was clear _ it was made up of four active <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> teams and three <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> teams _ the Soviets refused to say whether they were currently in the military or not, <PERSON> Iseminger </PERSON> said. The level of competence needed in the contest would not easily be obtained in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> without a military background. The international competition is open to civilians, and 38 crews from six nations participated. The Soviets came in second, the British third, French fourth and West Germans fifth. The competition is a grueling challenge that requires an immense amount of concentration, and precision in navigation, flying and timing. Competitors must fly through four events: a 150-kilometer navigation course; a 80-kilometer course that must begin and end at a specific time with a load dropped off during the exercise; a precision flying event; and a slalom and skill course. For example, during the 80-kilometer test, a crew is handed a packet five minutes before takeoff that contains exact takeoff and arrival times and the course route. Contestants must take off on time, arrive on time and then thread a glass bottle suspended on a 20-foot rope through a hole in a box, without breaking it. The Americans flew the OH-58 Kiowa scout helicopter, used primarily to spot targets for other helicopter gunships on the battlefield. The Soviets used the MI-2, or Hoplite, a utilitarian transport or combat chopper. `` It takes skills, but it really boils down to mental toughness, and who handles pressure best,'' said <PERSON> Iseminger </PERSON>. The pilot, who in his job checks on the capabilities of other pilots, said the testing is useful for a military pilot. `` It's like money in the bank,'' he said. `` You may not need to use these skills everyday, but you know inside yourself that you can use them when you need them.'' <PERSON> Hobbs </PERSON>, who tattled that his winning comrade was known as the `` ice man'' for his cool flying under pressure, said the Soviets appeared to have inferior training, and that he would n't worry about meeting such competitors in a war zone. `` I do n't think so,'' <PERSON> Hobbs </PERSON> said. `` Really, there was just something lacking. They just could n't cut the mustard.''
</TEXT>
