<HEAD>Nagasaki Nuclear Foes Protest U.S. Navy Port Call</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK3</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Protesters in <LOCATION> Nagasaki </LOCATION> trampled on a wreath offered by a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> captain who was seeking Saturday to commemorate victims of the atomic bombing of that city. About 50 chanting protesters, many survivors of the bombing, refused to allow Capt. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> frigate <PERSON> Rodney </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> to approach a large memorial statue in the center of <LOCATION> Nagasaki </LOCATION>'s Peace Memorial Park. The statue is dedicated to victims of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> atomic bombing of <LOCATION> Nagasaki </LOCATION> at the end of World War II. <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> and other crew members instead placed a wreath about 100 feet away from the statue. After they left, several protesters pushed the wreath over and stamped on it. National television broadcast scenes of the protest. The <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Senji </PERSON> <PERSON> Yamaguchi </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Nagasaki </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atomic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bomb </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Victims </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, as saying the group was protesting because of the possibility the ship was carrying nuclear weapons. The agency quoted <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> as saying he regretted the incident, but that it would not affect his friendship with the people of <LOCATION> Nagasaki </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> forbids the production, possession or introduction of nuclear weapons into its territory, but many people believe <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> ships routinely enter <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> with such weapons aboard. <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> <ORG