<HEAD>Government Prepares Emergency Plan to Slash Deficit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Soviet government has prepared an emergency 1990 budget aimed at cutting the deficit in half within a year and slashing capital spending to improve supplies of consumer goods. But the budget, to be introduced to the Supreme Soviet legislature, already is coming under attack by at least one leading reform-minded economist who says parts of it are too austere. Committees begin work Monday and the budget will be submitted to the full legislature when it goes back to work a week later. The 1990 budget will seek to cut the deficit from $ 192 billion to $ 96 billion, the <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported Saturday. The plan calls for slashing spending on new factories and production equipment by 30 percent while calling for an ambitious 6.7 percent increase in production of consumer goods, the <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> report indicated. Some of the country's most radical economists say many economic problems are based in the decades-old practice of setting high production targets that are not feasible and ignore the quality of the goods produced. Other legislation will call for the establishment of a Soviet securities market, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. But the report gave no details on that or actual figures included in the budget. In a nationwide television speech Sept. 9, President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said the government's program to work out of the deficit, consumer shortages and other economic ills `` may include unpopular, probably tough and even painful measures.'' He said the government led by Premier <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryzkhov </PERSON> would have to come up with a practical plan to eliminate consumer shortages that now encompass sugar, soap, meat, cigarettes and many other basic items. Many cities are rationing such items in an effort to halt hoarding. It was only a year ago that Soviet officials announced for the first time the country had any kind of budget deficit, and the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> passed a budget with a $ 58 billion deficit in a budget of almost $ 800 billion. However, much of the deficit was hidden by accounting tricks, and estimates of the 1989 budget deficit quickly mushroomed. One leading economist, <PERSON> Abel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aganbegyan </PERSON>, said in an article in the September issue of the monthly <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> that the plan to cut $ 153.8 billion in capital outlays by 30 percent is too severe. `` Speaking honestly the proposal ... frightens me,'' he wrote. `` I think this could lead to extremely negative consequences. You ca n't go from one extreme to the other.'' Soviet budgets for years have been burdened by huge outlays for new factories, buildings and equipment at the expense of basic consumer goods. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and his economic advisers now say much of the equipment and many of the buildings were unnecesary in the first place, and are operating inefficiently if at all. But <PERSON> Aganbegyan </PERSON>, an adviser to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, said the 1990 budget plan goes too far in cutting those expenditures. The Ministry of Oil and Gas Construction, for example, is planning to freeze millions of rubles worth of construction equipment and thousands of miles of pipeline and discharge 76,000 highly qualified workers, he wrote. The economist said the capital budget should be cut by about 20 percent, with $ 8 billion set aside to help Soviets finance private housing construction. The other $ 24 billion should be used to increase public housing construction, the number of private garden plots and family resorts, and set up a program to help consumers buy highly sought-after items such as cars, video equipment and personal computers, he said. The budget is likely to come under tough scrutiny by Supreme Soviet committees, which under the new government structure instituted this year have become much more critical of government programs.
