<HEAD>IG Report Says 31 of 54 Dams on Indian Lands Pose Serious Threat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At least 31 of the 54 dams operated by the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> pose a serious threat to life and property, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s inspector general. The report of Inspector General <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON> said the dams, all on Indians lands in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, are either in `` poor'' or `` unsatisfactory'' condition as a result of inadequate maintenance by the <ORGANIZATION> BIA </ORGANIZATION>. `` These unsafe dams, which pose a serious threat to hundreds of lives and surrounding property, could potentially cost hundreds of millions of dollars to repair,'' <PERSON> Richards </PERSON> wrote in a letter to <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON>. The report, released publicly over the weekend, has already been seen by <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON>, who has instructed Assistant Secretary for Indian Affairs <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> `` to take a look and take the necessary actions to have those dams repaired or maintained in proper order,'' <ORGANIZATION> BIA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> said Saturday. Assistant Inspector General <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloom </PERSON> wrote in the report: `` These dams have safety deficiencies, including serious problems with excessive seepage and embankment erosion, that are worsening each year because of a lack of maintenance. Most could not withstand a major flood, and, as a result are imminent threats to rural communities downstream.'' Among the worst examples, said <PERSON> Bloom </PERSON>, are the <LOCATION> Ganado </LOCATION>, Round Rock and Many Farms dams in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, the <PERSON> Pablo </PERSON> and Lower Dry Fork dams in <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Ponca </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dam </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>. Failure of the Pablo Dam, the largest in the Flathead Indian Irrigation Project in <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, could cause `` considerable loss of life _ potentially 400 people _ and excessive economic loss in the towns of <PERSON> Pablo </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dunham </PERSON> and adjacent subdivisions,'' <PERSON> Bloom </PERSON> said. His report noted that the <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION>, in a 1988 study on flood control on the <LOCATION> Navajo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reservation </LOCATION>, said of <LOCATION> Ganado </LOCATION> and six other dams in the area: `` It is virtually certain that these unsafe and often undersized dams will fail during a major storm.'' The 31 dams, most of which are not listed by state in report, are: <LOCATION> Ganado </LOCATION>, Black Rock, <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Lower </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fork </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Dulce </PERSON>, <PERSON> Rosebud </PERSON>, Round Rock, <PERSON> Jocko </PERSON>, <PERSON> Weber </PERSON>, Acomita, <LOCATION> Crow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>, Standing Rock No. 1, Many Farms, <LOCATION> Oglala </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Tufa </PERSON> <PERSON> Stone </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pablo </PERSON>, He Dog, Picacho, <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Parmelee </PERSON>, White Clay, <LOCATION> Washakie </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bonneau </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ponca </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Crow </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ana </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Tabor </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Tsaile </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Coolidge </PERSON>, <PERSON> Asaayi </PERSON>, <PERSON> Elgo </PERSON>.
