<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two weeks before Vietnamese troops are to withdraw from <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is in a quandary over what it should do to block the resurgence of the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, a group that murdered up to 2 million people in the 1970s, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and congressional officials say. `` Basically, what's happening is that most people are trying to figure out what to do since <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>,'' said a senior administration official, referring to the collapse of a 19-nation peace conference in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> last month. `` People are trying to absorb what went on,'' the official said, speaking only on condition his name not be used. `` What do we do when, and if, the Vietnamese complete withdrawal?'' Participants at the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> conference failed to come up with a political solution for easing tension among warring factions in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> after the Vietnamese leave. <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> has said it will pull its troops out by Sept. 30, ending a 10-year occupation. The vacuum has created the `` very real possibility that the genocidal <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> could battle its way back to power in <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION>,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Solarz </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on Asian and Pacific Affairs. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, an expert on <LOCATION> Indochina </LOCATION> and former scholar at the <ORGANIZATION> Carnegie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Endowment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pe