 President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> urged the Baltic republics to compromise with their minorities and settle the region's ethnic disputes, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported. The Soviet president spoke at a meeting with <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and government leaders from <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> released its report on the Wednesday meeting late Friday. `` All our problems should be tackled by joint effort in the framework of the federation,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said. All the country's 15 republics are tied together economically, culturally and through human contacts, he said. `` If we now allowed the situation to deteriorate to the point where these ties would start to break up, the republics and the whole country would be rolled back by decades,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said. He added that `` any attempt to infringe on citizens' rights on the ethnic basis should be regarded as contradicting the principles of Soviet statehood and humanism.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s social reforms, including greater tolerance of dissent, has fueled a wave of nationalism in the <ORGANIZATION> Baltics </ORGANIZATION> and other Soviet republics. The Baltics are seeking greater autonomy and freedom from Kremlin control. But the growing nationalism also has heightened tensions among ethnic Russians and other minority groups who live and work in those republics, and who claim they are targets of discrimination by the ethnic majority. Non-Estonian workers in that republic struck last month after the Estonian government passed rough residency requirements for voting and running for local office. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s conciliatory tone comes after the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZ