<HEAD>Arab League Calls for Cease-fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALY MAHMOUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JIDDAH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An Arab League committee called Saturday for an `` immediate and comprehensive'' cease-fire in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, but admitted it has no power to enforce the appeal. `` The Lebanese crisis will not be resolved by military means,'' <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> Foreign Minister Prince <PERSON> Saud </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Faisal </PERSON> read from the declaration of the <ORGANIZATION> Tripartite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> comprising <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>'s King Fahd, Moroccan King <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> II and Algerian President <PERSON> Chadli </PERSON> <PERSON> Bendjedid </PERSON>. It said the cease-fire is necessary `` to stop the bloodshed and establish an atmosphere conducive to assuring the return of security, stability and national reconciliation.'' The call followed a night of savage shelling duels in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> that killed 12 people and wounded 72 others. <PERSON> Saud </PERSON> could offer no guarantee for the success of this latest in a string of cease-fire efforts by the 22-member <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>. `` The committee possesses no weapons with which it would impose its will in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Saud </PERSON> said. But he said <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, whose troops are battling the Christians in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, supports the new peace plan. The declaration called on all parties to stop supplying weapons to the combatants and said the committee already has received `` positive responses in this regard.'' <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has been arming the Christians. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> backs <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s Moslems, who want a bigger share of power in the country traditionally dominated by the minority Christians A `` Lebanese <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'' to be headed by Algerian diplomat <PERSON> Lakhdar </PERSON> will implement and oversee the cease-fire, monitoring all ships reported to be carrying weapons or ammunition, <PERSON> Saud </PERSON> said. As soon as the security body begins its work, naval blockades would be lifted and <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> reopened, the declaration said. Ibrahimi is expected in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> on Sunday and also is to negotiate the location of a Sept. 30 meeting of the Lebanese parliament `` to discuss and prepare the National Reconciliation Charter.'' The Arab League has blamed the failure of previous peace efforts mainly on <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>'s refusal to withdraw its 40,000 troops from <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION> wants to link such a pullout to the withdrawal of Israeli troops in southern <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. `` In the final analysis all foreign non-Lebanese forces will have to leave <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Saud </PERSON>.
