<HEAD>Police Stand Back as Blacks Bury Slain Activists</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 20th pvs, ``He has ...'' to UPDATE with
minister named to talk to blacks; picks up 21st, pvs, ``In another ...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CPN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAHM VENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Activists pledged to expand their anti-apartheid campaign Saturday as they buried victims of election night violence in black and mixed-race townships outside <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>. Police were present at the four funerals Saturday, but kept a low profile as part of a new government policy not to disrupt peaceful demonstrations and gatherings. `` Death will not deter those struggling for a free <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>,'' the Rev. <PERSON> Lionel </PERSON> <PERSON> Louw </PERSON> told about 4,000 mourners at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Augustine </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Anglican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in the mixed-race township of Grassy Park. `` Do you see the blood of our martyrs? Can you hear them speak? These are atrocities committed against our people. We ca n't allow -LRB- police -RRB- brutality and call it law and order any longer,'' <PERSON> Louw </PERSON> said at the service for Pedro Page. Page, 18, was one of at least 23 people of black and mixed-race that activists say were killed the night of Sept. 6 in violence instigated by police. Police gradually have raised their figures in recent days and now say there were 10 deaths in black-on-black faction fighting and nine killings in which police may have been responsible. The mourners traveled two miles from the church to the cemetery, guided by young activists serving as volunteer traffic marshals. The only visible police were traffic officers, and some gave their bright orange vests to the marshals and watched from afar. Asked how he felt about the marshals taking over his job, one mixed-race policeman said, `` I think it's wonderful.'' In the past, police have placed tight restrictions on the funerals of activists and prohibited political speeches at the ceremonies. Two funerals were held in the black township of <LOCATION> Khayelitsha </LOCATION>, and prominent activist Rev. <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesak </PERSON> led a funeral service for 13-year-old <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Muller </PERSON> in the mixed-race township of <LOCATION> Bellville </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Boesak </PERSON> said activists would resume marches on `` whites-only'' beaches beginning Sept. 30 and would extend major protest actions to the southern cities of the eastern <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Province </LOCATION>. He called on the government not to act against a huge anti-apartheid convention set for Oct. 7 in <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>. The Mass Democratic Movement, a loosely-based anti-apartheid coalition, launched a nationwide campaign of defiance on Aug. 2. The organized demonstrations aimed at segregated schools, hospitals, beaches, buses and other facilities have been peaceful. However, spontaneous clashes have erupted repeatedly between young activists and police, particularly in the townships surrounding <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>. President-elect F.W. <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON>, in a major policy shift, announced Tuesday that the white-led government would not block peacful protests, which previously had almost always been banned. More than 20,000 people joined a <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> march Wednesday against police brutality, the largest such demonstration ever authorized by the government. About 15,000 chanting protesters marched through the heart of <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> and 2,000 took over the central square of the capital, <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>, on Friday. All the demonstrations have been peaceful and the only reported police action has been against white hecklers. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON>, who will be sworn in for a five-year term Wednesday, has portrayed himself as a reformer who wants to bring the 28 million black majority into the national government on a limited basis within five years. He has said he wants to begin negotiations with black leaders on a new constitution. But <PERSON> Boesak </PERSON> said conditions for such talks would include lifting the 3-year-old state of emergency, releasing political prisoners such as <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>, and legalizing organizations such as <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> guerrilla movement. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON> announced Saturday that <PERSON> Gerrit </PERSON> <PERSON> Viljoen </PERSON>, a former minister of black education, will spearhead the negotiations for the government. The Cambridge-educated <PERSON> Viljoen </PERSON>, 63, has a reputation as a bookish, soft-spoken, political moderate close to <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON>. In another development, Law and Order Minister <PERSON> Adriaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> will meet early this week with 40 mixed-race policemen, including Lt. <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Rockman </PERSON>. <PERSON> Rockman </PERSON> has become a folk hero among township youths since he began accusing police riot units of causing violence by beating protesters, bystanders and shoppers during anti-election demonstrations. `` -LRB- Police -RRB- are going to tag me as a terrorist and a Communist,'' <PERSON> Rockman </PERSON>, 30, said Friday at a memorial service for one of the victims of the election violence, 13-year-old <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Ras </PERSON>. But, he added, other policemen `` have the same ideas and views as me and this is a sign of hope for us in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. I know I am not alone.''
