<FIRST>r a AM-WaterWoes     09-16 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Water Woes,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Water Restrictions Are Sign of Times as Dry Season Nears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> already is in its worst dry spell since the 1950s and its annual six-month dry spell is less than two weeks away, meaning little relief can be expected before spring. With most of the state already under voluntary or mandatory water-use restrictions, the outlook of water managers, farmers and environmentalists has turned from caution to concern. `` We may go into the dry season with one of the lowest reservoir storage levels in recent history,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Broward </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON>. On Thursday, the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> board declared a water emergency and urged voluntary water cutbacks by almost 4 million people in <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Broward </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> counties. <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Okeechobee </LOCATION>, a principal source of drinking water for residents of southern <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, is about 3 feet below its normal level for this time of year. To boost the lake's level, the water board decided to pump farm water runoff into it. That runoff normally would flow south through the <LOCATION> Everglades </LOCATION>. Environmentalists attacked the so-called `` back-pumping,'' saying the phosphorus-rich runoff promotes algae growth that robs marine life of oxygen. The restrictions, which may become mandatory next month, include limiting car washing and lawn watering to three times a week between 4 a.m. and 8 a.m., said <PERSON> Tilford </PERSON> <PERSON> Creel </PERSON>, the deputy director of the district, which covers 16 counties from south of <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION> to the Keys. During the 12-month-old drought, responsible for extensive brush fires in the <LOCATION> Everglades </LOCATION> last year that occasionally shrouded <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> in smoke, rainfall has been below normal in all sections of the state, except the <LOCATION> Panhandle </LOCATION>. `` This is the all-time low in what we have for total surface water storage,'' said <PERSON> Creel </PERSON>. In the 16-county <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION>, which includes <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Petersburg </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, mandatory water restrictions have been in effect since February. The tough measures have generated some spirited vigilantism. In <LOCATION> Bonita </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, for example, the local newspaper has printed the names and addresses of residents ticketed for water violations. Penalties for violating the mandatory restrictions in the Palatka-based <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Johns </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> district could go as high as $ 500 and 60 days in jail, although most people receive only a warning for a first violation, said spokesman <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Albanesi </PERSON>. `` People just assumed the water was going to be there. But attitude is slowly beginning to turn around,'' he said.
