He displayed ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> appeared in public Saturday for the first time in more than three months, looking tan and healthy despite recent reports he was seriously ill or even near death. National television news showed the 85-year-old leader laughing, gesturing animatedly and walking steadily at the start of a 70-minute meeting at the Great Hall of the People with T.D. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, a Nobel Prize-winning physicist from <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. He displayed his bronzed hand to <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, and said he had been swimming for up to an hour a day in the sea. `` I do n't like indoor swimming pools,'' he was heard to say, `` but enjoy swimming in nature.'' <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> reportedly spent part of the past three months, among the most traumatic in Communist <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s history, at <LOCATION> Beidaihe </LOCATION>, a favorite resort for top officials along the northeast coast. <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s most powerful leader, has cut down on his public duties in recent years and has often disappeared for long periods, each time sparking rumors he is seriously ill. But this time both Chinese and foreign sources consistently reported that he was being treated for prostate cancer and may not have long to live. The lively <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> press in recent weeks reported <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> to be in a coma or already dead. <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>'s last public appearance was on June 9, when he congratulated martial law officers for their leadership in quelling what he called a `` counter-revolutionary rebellion'' intent on overthrowing the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the government. Troops stormed <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> June 3 and June 4, killing hundreds and perhaps thousands of people as they shot their way to student-occupied Tiananmen Square. <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> also is believed to have had the ultimate say in the decision, announced June 24, to purge <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> General Secretary <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON> and accuse him of splitting the party by supporting the pro-democracy goals of the student protesters. <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>, the top advocate of economic reforms initiated by <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> 10 years ago, has not been seen in public since May 19. He is believed to be under house arrest while the party decides whether to press criminal charges against him. <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>, in an apparent reference to <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>, said Saturday that `` some of our comrades just immersed themselves in their specific work, did not pay enough attention to ideological and political developments, were not vigilant enough against the serious corruption.'' `` The recent turmoil has taught us a major lesson,'' <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> said. `` After the turmoil, all of us have become sober-minded.'' <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>, whose support of economic reforms has generally been tempered by a hard line against political dissent, said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> will not change its policies of reform. But he added that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> must stick to socialism. `` There would be no new <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> today without the leadership of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> also echoed the conservative line on reform by saying production must develop at `` an appropriate pace,'' rather than the rapid pace preferred by <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> that is now being blamed for inflation and corruption. <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>'s comments, as carried by television news and the official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, did not specifically mention <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>. In 1987, <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> retired from all his official posts except the powerful chairmanship of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. However, he is still regarded as the only man powerful enough to maintain a truce among the party's different factions, and rumors of his death invariably raise fears of a destabilizing power struggle. In recent days, Chinese officials have suggested <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> was about to emerge in public, possibly to reassure the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> people before Oct. 1 _ the 40th anniversary of the <LOCATION> People </LOCATION><LOCATION> 's </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> _ that the government leadership is intact. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, a Chinese-American who won the Nobel Prize for physics in 1957 and is a frequent visitor to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, was not available for comment on his meeting with <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> or a luncheon afterwards. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> also met later with <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>'s successor as party chief, <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Zemin </PERSON>, who spoke of current efforts to help students `` enhance their political awareness and make a clear distinction between right and wrong.'' Those efforts include heavy doses of political education. <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> also told <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> that Chinese leaders have shown `` much concern'' for civilians injured or killed during the military takeover of the city. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> says about 300 people were killed during the clashes, but Chinese leaders have made no public statements of remorse for the bloodshed and the official media have not reported on civilians who lost their lives.
