<HEAD>Blacks and Whites Pay Tribute To Slain Guerrilla Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HEIDI VON EGIDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of people packed a church in a black suburb Saturday to pay tribute to <PERSON> Anton </PERSON> <PERSON> Lubowski </PERSON>, a leader in the Namibian nationalist movement who was assassinated outside his home. `` In a racially divided country such as ours, <PERSON> Comrade </PERSON> <PERSON> Anton </PERSON>'s role as a bridge builder will be sorely missed,'' said <PERSON> Theo-Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Gurirab </PERSON>, foreign affairs chief of the <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Lubowski </PERSON>, 37, was shot in the head with an AK-47 assault rifle outside his <LOCATION> Windhoek </LOCATION> home Tuesday night. Police are holding 50-year-old Irishman <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Acheson </PERSON> in connection with the killing, but no one has been charged. <PERSON> Lubowski </PERSON> was the only ranking white member of the Namibian nationalist guerrilla movement against South African rule. The Lutheran Church in the <LOCATION> Katutura </LOCATION> neighborhood was overflowing, and about 200 people listened from outside the church doors to the service for the man to be buried this week. <PERSON> Lubowski </PERSON>'s parents, his ex-wife and two children were there, along with several diplomats such as <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Renwick </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s ambassador to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> `` Nothing can justify so callous a murder of a man ... who devoted the best part of his time to fighting for a truly non-racial <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Gurirab </PERSON> said. `` Did it really have to happen now, at a time when his country and people needed him most?'' <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, which has been ruled by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> since 1915, is having elections in November expected to lead to independence early next year. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> agreed to implement independence under <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> supervision after signing a regional peace treaty last year that also calls for the withdrawal of <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s 50,000 soldiers from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, which waged a 23-year <PERSON> bush </PERSON> war for black majority rule, is favored to win the most votes. <PERSON> Lubowski </PERSON>, a prominent human rights lawyer, in 1984 became the first white to publicly declare his support for the guerrilla-backed organization. He joined its legal political wing and served as the group's unofficial spokesman in <LOCATION> Windhoek </LOCATION> while most of the leadership was in exile. Right-wing newspapers often ridiculed <PERSON> Lubowski </PERSON> for belonging to the leftist-oriented organization. <PERSON> Lubowski </PERSON> studied at two of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s best universities, <LOCATION> Stellenbosch </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>, and at one point was an officer in the South African army. His law practice was based in <LOCATION> Windhoek </LOCATION>, but he represented many anti-apartheid activists on trial in neighboring <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lubowski </PERSON> helped represent 14 blacks sentenced to death for the mob killing of a black policeman in 1985. Four days before <PERSON> Lubowski </PERSON>'s death, the 14 won an appeal to have their case retried.
