<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Explorers recovering gold that may value more than $ 400 million from a sunken ship off the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> coast said Saturday they also may have found two previously unknown species of marine life. Researchers using remote-control equipment gathered samples of the two organisms, apparently invertebrate animals, attached to remnants of the SS <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> at a depth of 8,000 feet, said <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Schatz </PERSON>, a director of the <ORGANIZATION> Columbus-America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Discovery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. The creatures will be studied on board and later taken ashore for further study, said <PERSON> Schatz </PERSON>, who spoke with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in a ship-to-shore telephone conversation from the Arctic Discoverer research vessel 200 miles offshore. The Central America sank during a hurricane Sept. 12, 1857, en route from <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. It was carrying a monthly shipment of gold from the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mint </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> banks by way of the Panamanian isthmus. The sinking claimed 425 lives; 153 people survived. Remnants of the wood and iron ship, discovered three years ago, lie on a section of ocean floor that <PERSON> Schatz </PERSON> said is a `` biological oasis'' in the midst of an otherwise barren area. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Herdendorf </PERSON>, an oceanographer from <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> who heads an onboard research team, said scientists have been trying to informally catalogue marine life seen around the wreck through television cameras. `` But these two were just total mysteries to me,'' he said in a ship-to-shore conversation. `` These looked really new.'' Conversations with specialists at the <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> heightened belief that the creatures were previously unknown, <PERSON> Herdendorf </PERSON> said. Both appear to be invertebrate animals similar to sponge or coral. They grow on stalks about eight to 10 inches long and may be part of the same family, he said. One consists of a narrow stalk that ends in plumes or polyps. The other has a coin-sized, fleshy growth extending off a central stalk. `` It may be the same organism in various life stages or it may be two different species,'' he said. The group planned to spend Saturday on scientific research, <PERSON> Schatz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Herdendorf </PERSON> said. In addition to collecting the two organisms, <PERSON> Schatz </PERSON> said, the group hopes also to catch other animals with traps baited with lobster from the group's dinner, scrape animals from the wreck hull and take a core sample of the sea floor. Though the first of the gold was found in August 1988, the Arctic Discoverer and its 21-member crew did not find the main gold deposit until Aug. 27 this year, after about a month at sea. <PERSON> Schatz </PERSON> said the team may be at sea for another month, and hopes to have the bulk of the gold up by then. As an offshoot of the commercial enterprise of recovering the gold, the group established an adjunct sciences program, headed by <PERSON> Herdendorf </PERSON>. More than a dozen researchers are now involved in the project, including scientists from the Smithsonian. `` The economic payoff is what pays for the science,'' <PERSON> Schatz </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Herdendorf </PERSON> said the group hopes to produce educational films and distribute their findings throughout the scientific community. `` It's really a dream. I guess the dream of all biologist is to find new life forms and advance the horizons of science. We're probably just beginning,'' <PERSON> Herdendorf </PERSON> said
