<HEAD>Polish Party Daily Says Soviets Repressed Millions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper Saturday said the Soviet invasion of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> in 1939 led to repression and crimes against millions of Poles. The paper, <PERSON> Trybuna </PERSON> <PERSON> Ludu </PERSON>, said the truth about the invasion must be told before Polish-Soviet relations can be put on a new basis. `` The date of Sept. 17 is deeply rooted in the consciousness of the Polish nation. Especially because the entering of Soviet troops was followed by growing repressions, and even mass crimes, which involved millions of Poles,'' the paper said. On Sunday, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> marks the 50th anniversary of the Soviet invasion, which came more than two weeks after the <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> army entered <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> at the outbreak of World War II. <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> had agreed to divide <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> into spheres of influence under secret protocols in the Ribbentrop-Molotov non-aggression pact on Aug. 23 of that year. Soviet troops are thought to have killed tens of thousands of Poles during the war. Another 1.5 million were deported to <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION> during the Soviet occupation. `` The crossing by the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> into the eastern borders of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> ... belonged for decades in our country to the most taboo subjects,'' the paper said. `` If Sept. 1 was the beginning of a cataclysm for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and later for the world, then Sept. 17 that year symbolizes a secondary blow that fell on our nation and the consequences of which were also enormous and tragic.'' Although Nazi aggression has been well publicized, the Soviet invasion was rarely mentioned in the official press for decades. It was, however, well documented in the unofficial or underground press. `` The truth about those events is deserved not only by the victims of the repressions, their descendents, the whole nation, but it is one of the important tasks in freeing Polish-Soviet relations,'' <PERSON> Trybuna </PERSON> <PERSON> Ludu </PERSON> said. Ceremonies were planned Sunday at the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, and there will be other smaller commemorations nationwide. Two years ago, a joint Polish-Soviet commission was set up to investigate `` blank spots'' in history such as the massacre of Polish officers at <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION>, the Soviet invasion of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, and the 1920 Polish-Soviet war. Last Aug. 23, deputies in the lower house of parliament passed a resolution condemning the Molotov-Ribbentrop pact as `` shameful.'' Earlier, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> had condemned the secret protocols as `` a flagrant violation'' of international law.
