<SECOND>AM-Disaster Payments,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Advancing Disaster Payment Compromise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Farm-state senators said Friday they hoped the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> would act quickly on a committee proposal that could mean larger disaster payments to winter wheat and cotton farmers who started a second crop after weather destroyed their first. Legislation approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Thursday night would change the way disaster assistance payments are calculated. Lawmakers have complained that an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> formula will penalize those producers, and in some instances mean farmers could receive no disaster payments even though they earned little or no profit on their second crops. The proposal is part of a broad budget-balancing package the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is expected to consider soon, but some farm-state members hope the disaster relief measure can be acted on separately. The problem stems from a nearly $ 900 million disaster relief package enacted last month. In an effort to prevent farmers from reaping double benefits, it required the department to reduce assistance payments to farmers by the value of any crop that replaced one ruined by bad weather. The legislation did not spell out how to determine the replacement crop value. The department decided to deduct 75 percent of the gross value of the replacement crop from the disaster payment a farmer would have otherwise received for losses on his first crop. The formula is supposed to account for production costs of the replacement crop, in effect coming up with a net value figure. However, lawmakers contended the does not account for regional differences in production costs. Under the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> proposal, farmers would have no payment reductions if their replacement crops failed to produce more than 40 percent of the average yield in their county. Those farmers harvesting more than that would undergo the 75 percent deduction only on the value of their replacement crops above the 40 percent yield threshold. Other provisions would require quick payment for acres not replanted, for which farmers would have to apply before Oct. 1.
