<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv18   09-16 0721</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 18,0744</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Monday, Sept 18</HEAD>
<HEAD>The NAIC Pleas For A Capital Gains Tax Cut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If a proposed capital gains tax cut would benefit mainly the very rich, as critics claim, then its benefits must be broadened if it is to receive popular support. That's not the only major problem facing the proposal, which last week won approval from the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is considering a different approach. Somehow, a compromise must be reached. With these and other considerations in mind, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Hara </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, whose membership includes 6,832 investment clubs, decided to write President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ill </LOCATION>. His proposals: _ Permit the first $ 25,000 of an individual's capital gains each year to be _ Grant a lifetime exemption of $ 500,000 in capital gains from stocks to an individual This would be in line with the precedent set for profits on home sales. _ Allow an individual to roll-over capital gains from securities into new investments without tax on capital gains until retirement age is reached And then tax only half those gains. _ Index capital gains to inflation These ideas might help, said <PERSON> O'Hara </PERSON>, because compromise must be reached not just in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, but between the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> feels a cut would encourage long-term investing. <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> chairman, thinks that over time it would deprive Uncle <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> of funds. The platform from which <PERSON> O'Hara </PERSON>'s proposals are made is an interesting one. Most <ORGANIZATION> NAIC </ORGANIZATION> clubs began with little money. In August, these clubs averaged 16.2 members and $ 65,000 in assets, to which they added $ 452.77 per club in contributions. As a group, therefore, they might have a small-investor view. But they also have some big-investor credentials. Some clubs have been very successful, helping members to buy houses and pay tuitions. As individuals, apart from their club membership, some members have portfolios that run into the millions of dollars. The association's viewpoint is further broadened by inclusion of 48,000 individual members in a low-cost investment program, in which investors buy their first share in a company through <ORGANIZATION> NAIC </ORGANIZATION>, and thereafter buy directly from that company on a monthly or quarterly basis. Average investment: $ 75 a shot. From <ORGANIZATION> NAIC </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Royal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> O'Hara </PERSON> said, `` We asked our members why they were not as active as individual investors as they had been in the past.'' The common response, he says, was that members were discouraged by the change <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> made in 1986 by taxing capital gains, plus they felt there was a lack of consistency in taxing policy. That struck at the <ORGANIZATION> NAIC </ORGANIZATION>'s foundation; it was created to attract ordinary folks into becoming investors, to get them to save and win rather than spend and lose, yet its own members showed a growing reluctance to invest. In short, though interested in stocks, members were becoming like the rest of the public. Thirty years ago the individual investor accounted for 80 percent of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trading. Now it's less than 20 percent. This situation, he feels, greatly reduces liquidity in the securities markets, reduces capital needed for smaller businesses and deprives individuals of the advantages that come with economic participation. Moreover, he says, <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> faces growing international competition. The cost of raising capital is much lower in many nations with which we compete, one reason being that some have no capital gains tax at all. `` It is clear to us that the less we have in the way of a capital gains tax, the lower the cost of capital will be in this country and the more competitive our industry will be,'' <PERSON> O'Hara </PERSON> wrote. He added a personal observation. `` I am 74 years old and have spent most of my life working with individual investors, encouraging them to save more and invest more. `` I write with the strongest personal conviction that there are only two things that can turn our nation of consumers into a nation of investors.'' One, he said, is a meaningful reduction in capital gains taxation. The other: Depression. The latter, he said, would be an incredibly painful lesson. The first, he wrote, `` will work beyond our greatest expectations.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Mon, Sept 18</NOTE>
