<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions Sept 16-17</HEAD>
<BYLINE>After Hot Summer For Stocks, An Autumn Chill? ^By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After the stock market's long summer rally, many analysts and money managers fear it is heading for an autumn fall. The fears started to rise even before the debt problems of <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> roiled the market for high-yield `` junk'' bonds in the past few days. They intensified when the news about <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> raised the question of whether stocks might catch a chill should takeover fever die down. But a vocal group of optimists persists in predicting new highs for the market above the peaks reached at the beginning of this month. Junk bond worries, they say, may prove nothing more than a convenient excuse for stocks to undergo a `` correction'' that sets the stage for a renewed advance. `` Memories of past Octobers have stirred up fears in almost every analyst we have heard in the past several weeks,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Leeb </PERSON> in his investment advisory letter Indicator Digest. `` While admittedly few are predicting a crash, many if not most feel that a correction of 10 percent or more is likely by the end of October. Yet not one of these pundits is predicting a concomitant rise in interest rates or big uptick in economic activity. `` This is akin to predicting that a rocket ship will blast off without any fuel in it. It just does n't work that way.'' For a significant decline in stock prices to occur, <PERSON> Leeb </PERSON> argues, `` you must have _ at a minimum _ a sharp rise in interest rates. And that is simply not in the cards.'' Many people who make the decisions at investing institutions such as pension funds came back from the Labor Day holiday in a wary mood, seeking ways to preserve the gains they racked up over the first eight months of the year. The most obvious way to do this is to `` raise cash,'' in Wall Street parlance, by selling some stocks and putting the proceeds in short-term money market investments. But <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> argues that the supposed safety in such a strategy could be illusory in a business where money managers are measured against their counterparts' performance and the market indexes `` The problem with trying to duck a correction today is that there appears to be very decent potential left on the table,'' he maintains. `` A decent bond outlook, a stable dollar and an economy without excesses is hardly the environment that makes stocks particularly dangerous. `` A correction may occur, given the sharp summer advance, but we view it as essentially unplayable. The fundamentals are too solid and the potential too high to try to sit on a lead.'' Wariness prevailed over enthusiasm in the past week, however, as stocks recorded their second straight loss after nine consecutive weeks of gains. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 34.96 to 2,674.58 on top of a 42.55-point loss the week before. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> composite index fell 2.36 to 191.59; the <ORGANIZATION> NASDAQ </ORGANIZATION> composite index for the over-the-counter market lost 3.74 to 467.57, and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> market value index was down 4.46 at 379.64. <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> volume averaged 165.52 million shares a day, against 155.31 million in the previous week. Emphatically not among the bulls on the stock market outlook is <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>, editor of the advisory service <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>'s Interest Rate Observer, who says: `` Stocks in general are strong. Yet junk bonds are markedly weak. How to explain the divergence? `` As always, the correct and certain answer is unknowable. However, we happen to have a hypothesis in the form of a prejudice, or guess: The stock market is kidding itself and is riding for a fall.''
</TEXT>
