<HEAD>NL Industries Changing Tactics on Georgia Gulf</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For Saturday PMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Companies controlled by billionaire <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> investor <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> are cutting their stake in <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and putting on hold a plan to oust the chemical concern's board In a filing with the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Friday, the Dallas-based <ORGANIZATION> Simmons </ORGANIZATION> consortium _ headed by <ORGANIZATION> NL </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> _ said it was cutting its <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> holdings to 8.9 percent of common stock outstanding. <ORGANIZATION> NL </ORGANIZATION> also said it wants to work with <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> in its `` pursuit of alternative transactions.'' Previously, <ORGANIZATION> NL </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> said it would seek written consents from shareholders to oust the board after it rejected an offer to acquire the Atlanta-based company or help it recapitalize, which would give shareholders at least $ 55 per share in cash. No further meetings between <ORGANIZATION> NL </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> are scheduled, the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> filing said. <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION>'s board announced on Thursday that it had asked investment banking firm <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to explore alternative transactions such as an acquisition or joint venture. Meanwhile, <ORGANIZATION> NL </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> and another <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> affilate, <ORGANIZATION> NL </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemicals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, have sold off 230,000 <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> shares over the last two weeks, cutting their holdings from 9.9 to 8.9 percent. <ORGANIZATION> NL </ORGANIZATION> controls 5.6 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION>'s outstanding common stock, whicle <ORGANIZATION> NL </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemicals </ORGANIZATION> has 3.3 percent. The shares were sold in blocks ranging from 6,300 shares to 33,500 shares for prices between $ 58.50 and $ 59.50 per share. The two <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> companies said they will continue selling shares if they stay above the $ 55 price they believe could be obtained through leveraged recapitalization, merger or other transaction. But <ORGANIZATION> NL </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NLC </ORGANIZATION> also said they would resume their dump-the-board plan in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> takes steps `` not reasonably calculated to realize'' at least $ 55 per share for stockholders.
