<FIRST>d f PM-Brady-NASD     09-16 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brady-NASD,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Treasury Secretary: Junk Bond Shakeup Won't Affect Stocks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For Saturday PMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> says investors should n't be worried about price drops in the junk bond market spreading to the stock market. `` I do n't think that's going to happen,'' <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> told a luncheon marking the 50th anniversary of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dealers </ORGANIZATION> on Friday. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> also defended the proposed cut in capital gains taxes but said he favored a reduction longer the 27 months contained in a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bill that passed through committee this week. The market in high-yield, high-risk bonds has been in tailspin since Wednesday, when retailing giant <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said it might not be able to make a major loan payment for one of its affiliates to avoid defaulting on its junk bond debt. Since then, panicky investors have dumped issues they deemed especially risky. But <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said junk bonds `` have a substantial assets base. This is n't just equity in disguise. There literally are assets behind it.'' `` So I do n't think it'll have an effect on the stock market,'' he added. After a brief speech, <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> answered several questions at the luncheon for <ORGANIZATION> NASD </ORGANIZATION>, the self-regulatory group that oversees the over-the-counter market of securities that are n't traded on nation's major stock exchanges He defended the proposed cut in capital gains _ profits from the sale of capital assets such as stocks or real estate _ approved by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday. The plan still must clear the full <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> as well as the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The plan approved by the committee would reduce the tax rate of 33 percent to 19.6 percent for the next 27 months. The tax rate then would rise to 28 percent but would be `` indexed'' to tax only increases exceeding the annual inflation rate. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said he wished the terms of the proposed tax were longer, `` but let's take what we can get and keep working on it,'' he said. Critics have called it a tax break for the rich, while supporters say it would help the economy by encouraging investment. `` People are beginning to understand that this not only benefits people who are in our industry, purchasing and selling securities,'' <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> told the crowd of about 300 stock and bond dealers, industry regulators and reporters. `` It benefits the guy who who starts a steel distribution business, with his $ 10,000 savings, in his garage and 38 years later sells it to somebody else for 750,000 bucks,'' he said. `` They're starting to understand that this is n't some sort of Wall Street benefit plan.
</TEXT>
